Notes for Indexing (for the report):

The preprocessing stage transforms raw textual data into a normalized token stream suitable for indexing. Following standard Information Retrieval practices (Manning et al., 2008), case folding, stopword removal, and optional stemming were applied prior to index construction. This ensures consistent term representation, reduces vocabulary size, and improves both indexing efficiency and retrieval effectiveness. The resulting token sequence is then used to construct a positional inverted index, enabling accurate term frequency statistics and phrase query support.

Why I built indexing like this (so you can explain it in the report)
1) Positional inverted index

You store term positions so you can do phrase queries (needed for "to be or not to be"). The classic IR approach is a positional index: term → docID → positions. This is standard in IR systems for phrase and proximity search.

2) Separate field indexes (title/author/body)

Your assignment explicitly requires search in structured data 

Assignment_1

. Metadata fields like title/author are structured, so we maintain separate indexes:

title_index: supports exact/field search (great precision)

author_index: handles "Philip K Dick" properly

body_index: supports TF-IDF and BM25 ranking on content

This also makes your Evaluation section much stronger because you can clearly show what structured search does well vs. unstructured models.

3) One-document-at-a-time processing

With ~76k books, you must avoid loading everything into memory at once. This design reads a file, preprocesses, indexes, and moves on.

4) Doc length and avgdl tracking

BM25 later needs:

document length dl

average document length avgdl

So we compute and store these during indexing.



