Why stop word removal is not done in my code :

Stopwords were retained in the body index to preserve positional consistency required for phrase query processing. Although high-frequency terms have limited discriminative power, ranking models such as BM25 inherently reduce their influence through inverse document frequency weighting.


Problems on disk while indexing and why we are using sqlite3?
Good catch — that's actually the flaw in the approach I proposed. Here's what 
  happens in that solution:
                                                                                
  1. During indexing: chunks are flushed to temp files on disk (e.g.
  /tmp/ir_index_/chunk_00001.pkl)                                               
  2. Merge step: all chunks are loaded back into RAM and merged into three final
   Python dicts (final_body, final_title, final_author)
  3. Those merged dicts (still in RAM) are wrapped into IndexBundle and then
  pickled to data/index/index_bundle.pkl
  4. Temp dir is deleted

  So the chunking only reduces peak RAM during the per-doc tokenization phase —
  it prevents holding all 42k books' token lists simultaneously. But the merge
  step loads all posting lists back into RAM anyway, meaning the final merged
  index still has to fit in memory before it gets saved.

  For the full 42k-book corpus, this doesn't fundamentally solve the OOM
  problem.

  What would actually solve it is keeping the index on disk throughout — never
  materializing the full index in RAM:

  - SQLite: write each (term, doc_id, freq) row directly as you process docs;
  query it at search time
  - On-disk merge sort: sort partial index files by term, then stream-merge them
   term-by-term and write directly to the output file without loading everything
   at once

  Both of those are significantly more complex than the current architecture.
  The honest short-term options are:

  1. Use limit_docs (e.g. 5000–10000) to build a smaller index that fits in RAM
  2. Switch to a proper on-disk index structure (SQLite is the simplest path)


SQLite — it's the right tool here for several reasons:                        
                                                                                
  1. Built into Python — no new dependencies (import sqlite3)                   
  2. Truly memory-safe — you write each (term, doc_id, freq) row directly to
  disk as you process each document; the full index is never in RAM             
  3. Scales to any corpus size — 42k books, 420k books, doesn't matter          
  4. At search time, load only what you need — e.g. fetch the posting list for
  just the query terms, not the entire index


The schema would be straightforward:

  body_index   (term TEXT, doc_id INTEGER, freq INTEGER)
  title_index  (term TEXT, doc_id INTEGER, freq INTEGER)
  author_index (term TEXT, doc_id INTEGER, freq INTEGER)
  doc_lengths  (doc_id INTEGER, body_len INTEGER, title_len INTEGER, author_len
  INTEGER)
  metadata     (doc_id INTEGER, title TEXT, author TEXT, language TEXT)


The one trade-off: if you want positions for phrase search, you'd store them
  as a compressed blob (e.g. array.array serialized to bytes) in an extra column
   — still fine on disk, just slightly more complex to deserialize.


Why not just save to disk earlier?

  A Python dictionary can only be saved all at once with pickle. You can't write
   half a dictionary to disk, clear the RAM, and continue. It's all or nothing.

  ---
  What SQLite gives you

  SQLite is essentially a file on disk that behaves like a table — and
  crucially, you can write one row at a time to it.

  So instead of:
  Build entire index in RAM → save to disk at the end (OOM)

  We now do:
  Process 500 books → write those rows to disk → clear RAM → repeat

  At any point in time, RAM only holds 500 books worth of data. The rest is
  already safely on disk in index.db.



